============================================================

Written to `tools/title-loop/docs/8-b5177f1/feedback.md`. Summary of findings:

**Baked Eggs (returns empty):**
The pre-merge correctly joins "Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce" + "& Coriander" into one candidate. It passes all hard filters. But the title contains ingredient-like vocabulary ("Harissa Tomato Sauce", "Feta") that raises similarity to `HEADER_REFERENCE`, potentially making `rawScore ≤ 0`. With no ALL_CAPS or structural bonus, it can fall below the 0.08 threshold — the only candidate in the pool gets silently discarded.

**Faszerowana papryka (wrong candidate selected):**
The first-line mixed-case protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this pattern — mixed-case Polish title at pos 0 followed by ALL_CAPS romanisation at pos 1. But the protection only fires when both candidates are already in `selected`. "PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM" gets +0.18 (allCaps + structural bonuses), inflating the threshold to a level the short Polish phrase can't reach alone. With "Faszerowana papryka" below threshold, `pos0 = null` and the protection never activates.

**Common themes:**
1. ALL_CAPS bonuses inflate the threshold, making the first-line protection self-defeating
2. Ingredient-bearing titles are penalised by embedding similarity to `HEADER_REFERENCE`  
3. No fallback when the candidate pool is unambiguous but scores are low
4. The first-line protection has a circular dependency: it's needed when the mixed-case title is outscored, but that's precisely when it can't fire
