h name. Unless the embeddings model gives it a weird score...\n\nBut wait, I don't have access to the actual embedding output. The analysis should be based on code logic.\n\nHmm, actually looking again at the result more carefully: \"Got: ''\" vs expected. Maybe the issue is completely different - maybe there's an issue with how the result is displayed (undefined → ''). The test shows \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander - no\", so it failed and the function returned something empty.\n\nWait, could the issue be simpler? Looking at the input text again, the pre-merge step checks if the second line \"& Coriander\" matches the pattern `/^[/&+:(]/`, and since it starts with \"&\", it should match that character class.\n\nNow I'm checking the garbled text detection logic more carefully. I'm looking at how it evaluates individual words in the merged text to see if any of them would be flagged as garbled.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be in the scoring phase rather than candidate generation. The merged candidate could be passing the garbled check but then getting filtered out because its position score falls below the threshold. rawScore could theoretically be negative if the embedding model rates the text as more similar to header or noise patterns than to actual recipe titles, which seems unlikely for well-formed titles but I can't rule it out without testing the actual embeddings. Let me step back and reconsider the overall approach here.\n\nLooking at the actual file structure, the title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" gets merged into a single line, but phrases like \"Harissa Tomato Sauce\" might trigger ingredient-like embeddings rather than title-like ones, potentially causing that negative rawScore issue. The real problem is that this should be a valid candidate passing the filters, yet the result comes back empty. Looking at the character count again—it's 54 characters, which passes the length filter. I'm 